<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<h4><b>31c09. Temporary help firms.</b></h4>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.25in'><span style=3D'font-size:1=
1.0pt'>The
typical temporary help firm (such as Peakload, Inc. and Manpower, Inc.) is
engaged in supplying workers employed by the firm on an “as needed” basis to
various establishments. A person who desires employment usually registers w=
ith
the temporary help firm. For certain types of jobs the registrant usually
voluntarily “shows up” at some central location where he awaits employment
opportunity. If work is available or becomes available, he is sent or taken=
 to
the customer’s establishment. If accepted by the customer, he remains and
performs the work of that employer. At the end of the day, the worker is fr=
ee
to go home and collect his pay later or to return to the central location t=
o be
paid for his work. The circumstances vary. If the employment understanding
clearly is that the pay or the time of the employee begins and ends at the
customer’s establishment, waiting for assignments at the central location o=
r in
travel from there to the customer’s establishment and return would not be
compensable worktime. In other words, his working time is computed in the s=
ame
manner as if he had gone directly from his home to the customer’s establish=
ment
and returned home from there at the end of the day. This would be true even
though he may be assigned to work at the same customer’s establishment for =
more
than one day.</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>ADD the following new=
 Sec to
text and Table of Contents. Also, REMOVE FOH Insert #1825 from the front of
Chapter 59 and DELETE the entry for #1825 on Form WH-100. INSERT #1835
(5/22/95)</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<h4><b>31c10. Compensability of travel time of employees who voluntarily dr=
ive
company vehicles between home and work sites.</b></h4>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>(a)<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>=
&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>Background:</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.5in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>(1)<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>=
&nbsp; </span></span><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>In some industries employers utilize somewhat mo=
dified
vans or trucks for use by employees who perform service work at a customer’s
home or business establishment. The vehicle provides a necessary means for =
the
employee to transport needed parts, tools, equipment, etc., to various work
sites during the day. The employer may give employees the opportunity to dr=
ive
the vehicle between home and work on a voluntary basis.</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.5in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>(2)<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>=
&nbsp; </span></span><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>In some instances, the employee starts the work =
day by
calling the employer’s dispatcher from home, receiving one or more work
assignments to begin the work day, and traveling directly from home to the
first work site rather than traveling first to the employer’s establishment=
 and
then to the work site. At the end of the day the employee may be required to
call the employer’s dispatcher to advise that the last service call for the=
 day
has been completed and that the employee is leaving the last work site for
home, where the employee parks and locks the vehicle. During this call to t=
he
dispatcher, the employee may or may not receive assignments for the next da=
y.</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.5in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>(3)<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>=
&nbsp; </span></span><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>WH policy on the compensability of travel time i=
n such
situations was set forth in an Administrator’s opinion letter dated August =
5, 1994.
In light of the concerns expressed by both employers and employees, and the
possible effects of applying this interpretation in a wide variety of
industries, the Secretary of Labor, on October 19, 1994, deferred any WH
efforts to enforce the policy in that opinion letter while a review was
undertaken.</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>(b)<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>=
&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>Policy:</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.5in'><span style=3D'font-size:11=
.0pt'>An
Administrator’s opinion letter was issued on April 3, 1995, which withdrew =
the
August 5, 1994, opinion letter and set forth WH’s position in this matter.
Accordingly, where the following circumstances exist, time spent traveling
between the employee’s home and the first work site of the day and between =
the
last work site of the day and the employee’s home need not be compensated:<=
/span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.5in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>(1)<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>=
&nbsp; </span></span><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>driving the employer’s vehicle between the emplo=
yee’s
home and customers’ work sites at the beginning and end of the workday is
strictly voluntary and not a condition of employment;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.5in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>(2)<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>=
&nbsp; </span></span><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>the vehicle involved is the type of vehicle that=
 would
normally be used for commuting;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.5in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>(3)<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>=
&nbsp; </span></span><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>the employee incurs no costs for driving the emp=
loyer’s
vehicle or parking it at the employee’s home or elsewhere; and</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal><span style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=3DMsoNormal style=3D'margin-left:.5in;text-indent:-.25in'><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>(4)<span style=3D'font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>=
&nbsp; </span></span><span
style=3D'font-size:11.0pt'>the work sites are within the normal commuting a=
rea of
the employer’s establishment.</span></p>

